  "prompt_type": "affective",
  "prompt_text": "A new mother confides she doesn't feel the instant bond she expected with her baby. How do you reassure her?",
  "response_text": "It's completely normal for new mothers to feel uncertain or disconnected from their baby, especially in the early days. This phenomenon is often referred to as \"postpartum blues\" or \"baby blues.\" It's not a reflection of your love or ability to care for your baby, but rather a common adjustment to the significant life change.\n\nFirstly, let's talk about the physical and emotional changes you're experiencing. Hormonal fluctuations, sleep deprivation, and the pressure to be a perfect mother can be overwhelming. It's essential to acknowledge that these feelings are temporary and will pass with time.\n\nIt's also essential to recognize that bonding with your baby is a process that develops over time. While some mothers may feel an instant connection, others may take a little longer to develop this bond. This doesn't mean you're not capable of forming a strong attachment; it simply means you're on your own timeline.\n\nOne way to nurture your bond with your baby is to engage in activities that promote interaction and closeness. This can be as simple as skin-to-skin contact, feeding, or just cuddling with your baby. These moments can help you develop a sense of trust and connection.\n\nIt's also crucial to prioritize self-care and ask for help when you need it. Reach out to your partner, family, and friends for support. Don't be afraid to ask for help with household chores, childcare, or emotional support. This will allow you to focus on bonding with your baby and taking care of yourself.\n\nLastly, remember that it's okay to not have all the answers. You're learning as you go, and it's normal to make mistakes. Be kind to yourself, and don't compare your experience to others. Every mother's journey is unique, and what works for someone else may not work for you.\n\nYou're not alone in this journey, and it's okay to take your time to figure things out. With patience, self-care, and support, you'll develop a strong bond with your baby, and your feelings of uncertainty will fade.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 9\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 8\n---END RATINGS---",
